:''This article deals with "West Uvean" or "Fagauvea", a language of New Caledonia. For "East Uvean" or "Fakauvea", the language of Wallis Island (Uvea), see [[Wallisian language]].
{{Infobox language |name=West Uvean |nativename=Fagauvea |states=[[New Caledonia]] |region=[[Ouvéa]] |speakers={{sigfig|2220|2}} |date=2009 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Polynesian languages|Polynesian]] |fam5=[[Futunic languages|Futunic]]? |fam6=Emaic |iso3=uve |glotto=west2516 |glottorefname=West Uvean }}
'''West Uvean''' (also '''Uvean''' or '''Faga Ouvéa'''; ''Fagauvea'' in the vernacular) is a [[Polynesian language|Polynesian]] [[Polynesian outlier|outlier language]] spoken on the island of [[Ouvéa]], in the [[Loyalty Islands|Loyalty]] island group of [[New Caledonia]], and in the capital of Nouméa. It has long been in contact with [[Iaai language|Iaai]], the [[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic language]] also spoken on the same island. Consequently, four vowels have been added, and the syllable structure has become complex, allowing for final consonants.<ref name=Button>{{cite book|title=Language contact and change in the Austronesian world|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|date=1994|author1=Button, Tom|author2=Tryon, Darell T.}}</ref>{{rp|534}}
West Uvea is the only Polynesian language to use a [[quinary]] numeral system. It is probably the original decimal Polynesian people influenced by the nearby [[Iaai people]] who used a quinary numeral system, and changed from a decimal system to a quinary one. There are two sets of numerals from 11 to 20, the second way was the archaic form. The word 'tupu' means 'sum', 'teanua' in 'tahi a teanua' means 'human body', 'nea' in 'tahi enea' means 'man'. Nowadays, the West Uvea or Faga Uvea people use [[French language|French]] or [[Iaai language|Iaai]] numeral systems more frequently.
==Name== The speakers designate their language by the name '''Fagauvea''', which is also the name used in French. The name ''West Uvean'' sometimes used in English is meant to distinguish the language from the related ''East Uvean'' or [[Wallisian language|Wallisian]], spoken on [[Wallis Island]] ({{okina}}Uvea).
